directory: crates
summary: The workspace root for all CTX tooling crates. Together they form a layered system: `ctx-core` supplies the shared access-control primitive; `ctx-access` enforces it at the file I/O boundary; `ctx-cage` sandboxes agent subprocesses; `ctx-summarize` drives LLM-based `.ctx` generation; and `ctx-check`/`ctx-verify` run and report on code-quality checks.
children:
  - ctx-core: Shared deny-by-default access gate; the single canonical denylist consumed by all other crates.
  - ctx-access: Enforced file I/O binary for agents — reads, writes, and listings gated by ctx-core rules.
  - ctx-cage: bwrap sandbox host/proxy with a binary wire protocol; isolates agent tool invocations at the OS level.
  - ctx-summarize: LLM-driven `.ctx` and `rollup.ctx` generation pipeline with injectable Fs/Agent seams.
  - ctx-check: Standalone cargo/clippy/fmt/script check runner that emits a capped JSON diagnostic report.
  - ctx-verify: Alternate check-and-report pipeline with a `Runner` seam, strict exit codes, and synthesized hints.
key_invariants:
  - `ctx-core` is the sole source of access-control logic; no crate duplicates or bypasses its denylist.
  - All agent file I/O must flow through `ctx-access`; no crate performs direct filesystem access on behalf of agents.
  - Sandbox enforcement (`ctx-cage`) and access enforcement (`ctx-access`) are independent layers with no shared state.
intent_divergence: `ctx-check` and `ctx-verify` appear to duplicate the check-and-report responsibility; no intent.md clarifies which is canonical.